Before you judge this project, I want to say something honestly.

This is my first real piece of code. Yes, I used AI to help me build it. I am not pretending that I wrote every line by myself or that I suddenly became an expert programmer overnight. This project is not a masterpiece, and it is definitely not perfect. It is simply my first step.

For a long time, programming looked like a giant wall of confusing symbols, errors, and things I did not understand. The easiest thing would have been to stay away from it and keep saying, “I’ll learn later.” But instead, I decided to start. I used AI as a guide because beginners need guidance. Every developer learns from something: tutorials, books, teachers, friends, documentation, or examples on the internet. AI was my starting point.

What matters to me is not that I had help. What matters is that I was curious enough to try. I installed Python, fought with errors, fixed microphone issues, learned how packages work, learned how environment variables work, and finally built something that actually runs. The first time Drogon responded to my voice, it felt less like a program and more like proof that I could learn this.

I know this code may not be clean. It may not be optimized. A professional developer could probably rewrite parts of it in a much better way. And honestly? That is completely okay. This repository is not a declaration that I have mastered programming. It is a record of where I began.

Today I used AI to help me write code. Tomorrow I want to understand more of it. Next month I want to modify it myself. Eventually I want to write features from scratch without needing as much help. The goal is not to stay dependent forever; the goal is to learn enough that one day I can build my own ideas confidently.

So if you are looking at this repository, do not see it as “a project made by AI.” See it as a beginner learning how to create. Everyone starts somewhere. Some people start with a blank screen, some start with a tutorial, and I started with a dragon named Drogon and a lot of curiosity.

And yes… I am fully aware that my future code will probably contain some absolute nonsense, weird experiments, broken features, and a few “what was I thinking?” moments. But that is part of learning. I am looking forward to writing more code, breaking more things, fixing them, and slowly turning this first messy project into the foundation of something much bigger.

This is not the end of the journey. This is the first commit. 🐉💻
